	\'95	Learning system: your Noetherian contract wraps each block with (algebra, group, invariant form, integrator, charges). Conservation penalties and invariance tests run per layer during training.\
	\'95	Quantum offload (optional, gated): we add a TritFabric \'93quantum\'94 lane that calls Qiskit Primitives (Estimator/Sampler). Use it only where topology helps and error-mitigation is effective. Default remains local Aer simulators; hardware targets are opt-in.\
\
Where quantum helps\'97concretely\
	1.	Invariant estimation by sampling (U(1), SU(2) blocks)\
Some Noether charges boil down to expectation values of Pauli sums (e.g., angular-momentum proxies for SU(2) quaternion blocks). Those can be compiled to IBM\'92s heavy-hex connectivity with the native basis \{ECR, RZ, SX, X\} and estimated via Estimator with readout mitigation (M3) or ZNE. This is a natural fit for Heron-class devices (low error, 100\'96150 qubits window).    \
	2.	Symmetry projection / equivariance checks\
To enforce \'93f(x)=f(g\'b7x)\'94 you can schedule paired circuits U_g vs identity and compare observables; Estimator\'92s error-mitigation knobs let you see the symmetry break amount more clearly than on noisy raw counts. This is especially useful for shallow circuits on heavy-hex (low SWAP depth).   \
	3.	Combinatorial side-problems (QAOA)\
Routing, schedule selection, or low-rank bracketization (octonion penalties) can be cast as Max-Cut/Ising subproblems and attacked with QAOA compiled to heavy-hex graphs. Pick larger devices (Osprey/Condor) for wider but shallow QAOA; pick Heron if you need deeper but narrower circuits.   \
	4.	Dynamic-circuit guards for conservation\
Mid-circuit measurements let you early-terminate or branch when a monitored charge drifts\'97mirroring your discrete Noether \'93gate.\'94 IBM\'92s System Two stack + primitives supports this dynamic style with mitigation baked into the workflow.   \
\
Everything above remains optional and reproducible offline (Aer). You only toggle real hardware when the mitigation curve makes it worth it.\
\
Which IBM machines to use (by topology + task)\
	\'95	Heron (
\f6 \uc0\u8764 
\f1 133\'96156 qubits, heavy-hex; System Two modules): Best error rates; good for deeper, structured SU(2)/U(1) expectation estimation and dynamic-circuit checks on 10\'96100 qubits. Use for invariant estimation & symmetry tests with Estimator+M3.   \
	\'95	Osprey (433 qubits, heavy-hex): Wider but noisier; use for shallow, wide QAOA or kernel feature maps where you care more about width than depth.  \
	\'95	Condor (1121 qubits, heavy-hex): Budget for very shallow breadth-first trials or layout studies; mitigation will dominate\'97treat as exploratory.  \
\
Why heavy-hex matters: IBM\'92s devices are laid out on heavy-hex lattices (degree-3/2 mix) to reduce crosstalk; compilers insert SWAPs to respect this graph. Plan circuits (and QAOA cost graphs) with that sparse coupling in mind for lower depth and better fidelity.  \
\
Mitigation you\'92ll actually use: Qiskit Runtime\'92s Estimator exposes toggles (M3 readout mitigation, dynamical decoupling, twirling, ZNE). Use them\'97don\'92t roll your own.   \
\
